---
# REQUIRED — must match legacy `articles.data[].id` when migrating (URL: /research/<slug>)
slug: your-article-slug

# REQUIRED — same as legacy `name`
title: "Your article title (use quotes if it contains : colons)"

# REQUIRED — publish date; use YYYY-MM-DD or ISO 8601 (maps to `createdAt`)
date: 2024-01-15

# REQUIRED for cards — same role as legacy `description` (shown on /research list)
summary: >-
  One or two sentences for the research index card. Folded YAML (`>-`) strips
  the single newline; use a blank line in the body for longer abstracts.

# OPTIONAL — YAML list of strings
tags:
  - topic-one
  - topic-two

# OPTIONAL — URL string, or "" (same as legacy `resume`; shown as “View Resume” when non-empty)
resume: ""
---

<!--
  BODY = Markdown + optional KaTeX.
  Remove this HTML comment block in real articles.
-->

## Summary / abstract

Short standalone summary for readers (the **summary** in frontmatter is for the card only).
You can repeat the gist here with **bold**, *italic*, and [external links](https://example.com).

## Section with inline math

The Schrödinger equation often appears as $i\hbar \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Psi = \hat H \Psi$.
Use single dollar signs for inline math.

## Display (block) math

Centered mathematics on its own lines:

$$
\nabla \cdot \mathbf{E} = \frac{\rho}{\varepsilon_0}
$$

## Example table (GitHub-flavored Markdown)

| Symbol | Meaning | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| $\hbar$ | reduced Planck constant | inline in cells is OK |
| $\Psi$ | wavefunction | |

## References

1. Author A. *Title of work.* Journal **Vol**, pages (Year). DOI or URL if allowed.
2. Author B. *Another reference.* See [arXiv:xxxx.xxxxx](https://arxiv.org/abs/xxxx.xxxxx).

## Notes

> **Note:** Use blockquotes for warnings, conventions, or editorial notes.
> Keep headings consistent (`##` / `###`) so typography stays uniform.

---

